Ensure code quality through automated tests. We use the following tools:
-  Jest : Testing framework for both frontend and backend.
-  React Testing Library : To test React components from a user perspective.
-  Supertest : For API endpoint testing.

 Running tests locally: 
```bash
npm run test           # run all tests once
npm run test:watch     # watch mode (re‑runs on file changes)
npm run test:coverage  # run tests and generate coverage report
```

 Coverage requirements: 
- Any new feature must achieve at least 80% coverage for the new code.
- Critical code (e.g., authentication, payment modules) requires 90% coverage.
- You can view current coverage in the `/coverage` folder after running the command.

 Writing tests – React component example: 
```jsx
// ArticleCard.test.jsx
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import ArticleCard from './ArticleCard';

describe('ArticleCard', () => {
  it('displays the article title', () => {
    render(<ArticleCard title="Hello" />);
    expect(screen.getByText('Hello')).toBeInTheDocument();
  });
});
```

 API testing (server): 
```javascript
// article.test.js
const request = require('supertest');
const app = require('../server');

describe('GET /api/v1/articles', () => {
  it('returns a list of articles', async () => {
    const res = await request(app)
      .get('/api/v1/articles')
      .expect(200);
    expect(Array.isArray(res.body.data)).toBe(true);
  });
});
```

 End‑to‑End tests: 
- Using Playwright or Cypress (depending on the feature).
- Run locally: `npm run test:e2e` (make sure the app is running first).
- These cover basic user flows (login, send message, change theme).

 Postman collection for API testing: 
Inside the `/postman` folder you will find a file `Bo-Chat-API.postman_collection.json`. You can import it into Postman and easily test all endpoints. It includes environment variables and pre‑request scripts.

 Tips for writing good tests: 
- Test the behavior of the function, not internal implementation details.
- Use clear descriptions (they should explain what you are testing).
- Isolate tests from each other (do not rely on state from a previous test).
- Review coverage periodically and add tests for uncovered code.

 CI test infrastructure: 
- For every PR, tests are automatically run via GitHub Actions.
- If any tests fail, the PR will not be merged until they are fixed.
- The report is visible directly on the PR page.

You are encouraged to add tests for any new code you contribute. If you need assistance, refer to the testing guide in `/docs/testing.md`.
